SUMMARY: Sampling Rate Effects
=================================================================
  Sampling Rate  |  Ts (s)  |  Gain Margin (dB) | Phase Margin (deg)
----------------+----------+-------------------+--------------------
  Continuous     |   N/A    |      Inf        |      -46.78
  f = 1 * f1    |  9.802441 |      Inf        |      Inf
  f = 3 * f1    |  3.267480 |      Inf        |      -109.75
  f = 10 * f1    |  0.980244 |      Inf        |      -64.90
----------------+----------+-------------------+--------------------

--- Effect Analysis ---
1. At f = f1 (lowest sampling rate):
   - Sampling frequency equals crossover frequency.
   - Nyquist frequency (0.05 Hz) is below/at signal content.
   - Significant aliasing and frequency response distortion expected.
   - Discrete system poorly matches continuous system.

2. At f = 3*f1:
   - Nyquist frequency (0.15 Hz) exceeds crossover frequency.
   - Basic Nyquist criterion satisfied.
   - Moderate accuracy improvement over f = f1 case.

3. At f = 10*f1:
   - High sampling rate provides good approximation.
   - Frequency response closely matches continuous system up to high frequencies.
   - Phase lag from ZOH discretization is minimal in the frequency range of interest.

--- Conclusion ---
Higher sampling rates yield more accurate frequency response matching.
A sampling rate of at least 10 times the crossover frequency is recommended
for accurate digital control system implementation.

Task 3 completed successfully.
